<div class="text-content w3-display-container">
    <h3>Making a character 101</h3>
    <hr>
    <ol>
        <li>Select a race from the Races Tab and fill that out on your sheet</li>
        <li>
            Fill in the information from the starting stats, abilities/powers, and starting 
            spells from the race of your choice and fill them out on your sheet.
        </li>
        <li>
            Change your characterâ€™s attributes(Health, Magicka, 
            Stamina, Defense, Magic Resist) accordingly if the 
            race has any starting changes to those attributes.
        </li>
        <li>
            You start yourself out with 75(dm can decide) experience points to set up your DnD roll 
            stats(strength,dexterity,etc). Follow the exp guide rules for this.
        </li>
        <li>You also start out with 250(dm can decide) gold to use throughout the start of your journey.</li>
        <li>
            For your equipment, you can start out with any novice grade(first option at the top of each 
            the weapon/armor lists ex. Iron Mace; Iron Greatsword; Long Bow). 
            If there is a starting armor of that same type that has the same defense, you can choose that 
            as well to start out with(ex. Imperial armor is the same as Iron armor so you can choose either one). 
            If you want a shield the same rules apply(hide shield/dented iron shield/guard shield are your first 
            options). If wearing clothes instead of any armor suits you better, do that :)
        </li>
        <li>Be sure to catalog your equipment under each list on your sheet</li>
        <li>Now all you need is a name for you character and then you're all set!</li>
    </ol>									 			
</div>

<div class="text-content w3-display-container">
    <h3>EXP/Leveling Guide</h3>
    <hr>
    <p>
        There will be three things you will get at the end of every session(dms decision). 
        The first thing you can get is for the new skyrim based system(skyrim levels). Here are the rules for those:
    </p>
    <ol>
        <li>
            For every skyrim level you get you change your three main attributes(Health, Magicka, and Stamina) 
            by adding 10 to the max value for that attribute(ex. Add 10 to max health to make the max health 110). 
        </li>
        <li>
            You get 2 skill points per skyrim level to use to level up your skills(Illusion, Smithing, 
            Light Armor, etc.). You use the level of your skills to unlock perks, which are additional 
            bonuses to enhance gameplay for a certain perk. You get 1 perk point per skyrim level.
        </li>
        <li>
            To unlock a certain perk, refer to the Perks tab to see if you meet the certain 
            requirements for a perk and if you do meet them as well as have any perk points 
            you can unlock the perk and catalog it to your list of perks.
        </li>
    </ol>
    <p>
        The second thing you can get at the end of a session will be exp points(for DnD rolls stats). 
        Here are the rules for those:
    </p>
    <ol>
        <li>To add 1 to any new roll stat the cost will be 5.</li>
        <li>
            To upgrade any roll stat that is not new the cost will be 5x the 
            current stat(ex. to upgrade a strength 2 to strength 3 it would cost 10 exp).
        </li>
        <li>There is no cap to how high an individual roll stat can be.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>The third thing you can get is gold which is obviously just currency.</p>
</div>

